# Licensing and attribution

CYD Palm is dual-licensed by component. The two halves have different obligations
because only one of them incorporates third-party GPLv3 assets.

## The on-device firmware (`firmware/`) — GPLv3

The firmware is licensed under the **GNU General Public License v3.0** (see the
root [`LICENSE`](LICENSE)).

It is GPLv3 because it reuses assets derived from **PumpkinOS**
(https://github.com/migueletto/PumpkinOS), which is GPLv3:

- **Bitmap fonts** — the PalmOS system fonts, converted to LVGL fonts
  (`firmware/main/lv_font_palm.c`, `firmware/main/lv_font_palm_bold.c`).
- **Launcher / silkscreen icons** — the Palm app and silkscreen bitmaps
  (`firmware/main/palm_icons.c`, `firmware/main/palm_icons.h`).

It additionally embeds a **kana bitmap font** and the Kana app icon
(`firmware/main/lv_font_kana.c`, the `icon_kana` bitmap in
`firmware/main/palm_icons.c`) derived from **IPAGothic** (IPA Font,
https://moji.or.jp/ipafont/), distributed under the **IPA Font License v1.0**.
Only a hiragana/katakana subset is rasterized into an LVGL bitmap font; the
original TTF is not redistributed. IPAGothic is © Information-technology
Promotion Agency, Japan (IPA).

PumpkinOS was also used as a *format and layout oracle* (a reference for the Palm
PDB record layouts and app screen structure) when writing the clean-room codecs
below; no PumpkinOS source code is compiled into the host bridge.

## The host bridge (`bridge/`) — MIT

The headless Palm ↔ CalDAV/CardDAV codec and sync engine under `bridge/` is
**clean-room** — written from the documented Palm database layouts, not copied
from PumpkinOS — and is licensed under the **MIT License** (see
[`bridge/LICENSE`](bridge/LICENSE)) so the codec can be reused freely.

Note: when `bridge/` sources are compiled *into the firmware* (as an ESP-IDF
component), the resulting device binary is a combined work and is covered by the
firmware's GPLv3. The MIT grant applies to the `bridge/` sources on their own
(e.g. the host `bridge_cli` tool and anyone reusing the codec elsewhere).

